The Telegraph - Calcutta : Opinion
Archives
							 																						DIVINE OVERTURES In an India caught between its age-old multiculturalism and a confused global culture, festivals are a return to those roots that are little understood and quickly forgotten today. Soumya Sitaramans FOLLOW THE HINDU MOON: A GUIDE TO THE FESTIVALS OF SOUTH INDIA (Random House, Rs 3,500) is a practical handbook in two volumes that almost clinically dissects South Indian religious festivals, timed according to the lunar cycle. From the sankalpa or invocation that begins a puja (extreme left) to traditional kolam art drawn to ward off evil spirits (top right), from the multifarious utensils used to cook the festival food (bottom left) to the elaborate feast lunch (bottom right) enjoyed after the puja  Sitaraman details all aspects of worship. However, the simplistic, textbook precision with which she writes, though informative, does little for reading pleasure. 
